en","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, which is of Norman origin, a coalescence of two different surnames, one derived from a Germanic personal name based on the element <i>war(in)</i> ‘guard’ and the other from a place in Normandy called <i>La Varenne</i> ‘the game park’. The Norman personal name survived at least into the 17th century in Yorkshire, where it was particularly associated with the Scargill family. In America this name has sometimes been chosen in honour of  General Joseph Warren , the first hero of the American Revolution, who was killed at  Bunker Hill  (  1775 ). Among modern influences on the choice of the name has been the film actor  Warren Beatty  (  b. 1937 )."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":9,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705190,"age":40,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Warren de Archdeacon was born about 1250, his father, William John Phillpotts L'Arckendeke, was 32 and his mother, Cecil de Haccombe, was 32. He married Elizabeth Talbot in 1269, in Tintagel, Cornwall, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died on 3 August 1307, in Devon, England, at the age of 58."},"et":{"about 1250–3 August 1307":"umbes 1250–3. august 1307","1250–1307":"1250–1307","1256–1307":"1256–1307","1274–1303":"1274–1303","1220–Male":"1220–Surnud","1220–Female":"1220–Surnud","about 1250":"umbes 1250","